The shell is going to cache and reuse ClientKey in 3.6. We should do the same in drivers. From SERVER-26952 ticket : 

SCRAM, by design, consumes a great deal of CPU resources while performing authentication. This can be a problem while populating connection pools, where many clients are authenticating at once. Fortunately, most of the expensive computations of SCRAM can be reused across multiple authentication requests. [RFC5802|https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5802#section-5.1] makes provisions for this:
{quote}
Note that a client implementation MAY cache ClientKey&ServerKey (or just SaltedPassword) for later reauthentication to the same service, as it is likely that the server is going to advertise the same salt value upon reauthentication. This might be useful for mobile clients where CPU usage is a concern.
{quote}

    {panel:title=Downstream Change Summary|titleBGColor=#239eb0|bgColor=#c2d2c2}
    This change adds a new optional field, "remoteOpWaitMillis" to the profiler / slow query log lines.  It tells you how much time the node spent waiting for results from other nodes.  By comparing this with the total "durationMillis" you can figure out whether the merger or a shard is to blame for a slow query.

It only appears when the command is an aggregate or a getMore on an aggregation cursor.  It only appears on the merging node.
    {panel}
    h2. Description of Linked Ticket
    Aggregation queries using $mergeCursors communicate with other shards and therefore can be affected by communication issues or issues on other nodes. In the following example the query ran for a very long time but did not spend any time acquiring locks and did not yield. Possibly it was waiting for a reponse from one or more of the other hosts, but there is no indication of that in the log message. It would be helpful for diagnosis if the slow query report indicated how much time was spent waiting for each host.

{noformat}
2017-06-23T06:53:15.357+0200 I COMMAND  [conn44] command ... command: aggregate { aggregate: "...", pipeline: [ { $mergeCursors: [ { host: "...", ns: "...", id: 253733414549 }, ...]}, { $group: ... } keysExamined:0 docsExamined:0 numYields:0 nreturned:0 reslen:17527 locks:{ Global: { acquireCount: { r: 6 } }, Database: { acquireCount: { r: 3 } }, Collection: { acquireCount: { r: 2 } } } protocol:op_command 2909221ms
{noformat}

    {panel:title=Downstream Change Summary|titleBGColor=#239eb0|bgColor=#c2d2c2}
    The reIndex command can now only be run on a standalone mongod.
    {panel}
    h2. Description of Linked Ticket
    Trying to run the 'reIndex' command on a secondary while having unfinished prepared transactions will hit an invariant. After dropping the index that will be re-indexed, we hit an invariant when doing a collection scan to insert all the documents in the collection for that index.
{code:java}Invariant failure lock.mode != MODE_S && lock.mode != MODE_X {6917529027641081857: Global, 1} in X src/mongo/db/storage/wiredtiger/wiredtiger_prepare_conflict.h 111
{code}
[~ldeng] recommended to try set the 'canIgnorePrepareConflicts' flag to true for the 'reIndex' command but that ended up hitting another invariant while trying to drop all the indexes.
{code:java}WiredTiger error (95) [1572545292:296845][8488:0x7f381342b700], file:_mdb_catalog.wt, WT_CURSOR.insert: __wt_txn_modify, 463: Transactions with ignore_prepare=true cannot perform updates: Operation not supported Raw: [1572545292:296845][8488:0x7f381342b700], file:_mdb_catalog.wt, WT_CURSOR.insert: __wt_txn_modify, 463: Transactions with ignore_prepare=true cannot perform updates: Operation not supported

Invariant failure: ret resulted in status UnknownError: 95: Operation not supported at src/mongo/db/storage/wiredtiger/wiredtiger_record_store.cpp 1442
{code}

We should consider disallowing the 'reIndex' command from running on secondaries and removing it in a future release.

    {panel:title=Downstream Change Summary|titleBGColor=#239eb0|bgColor=#c2d2c2}
The $out aggregation stage now supports outputting to a different database. It still accepts the old form of 

{noformat}
{$out: <collName>}
{noformat}

To use a different database, the new syntax is 

{noformat}
{$out: {db: <dbName>, coll: <collName>}}
{noformat}

    {panel}
    h2. Description of Linked Ticket
    The implementation has already been created and tested as part of SERVER-42693. The exposure could be achieved by adding syntax to $out and removing the _internal stage.

    {panel:title=Downstream Change Summary|titleBGColor=#239eb0|bgColor=#c2d2c2}
    We added a new accumulator operator called $accumulator.  This allows user-defined functions (Javascript) to run in a $group, $bucket, or $bucketAuto stage.
    {panel}
    h2. Description of Linked Ticket
    Implement the $accumulator operator, which will let users create their own accumulators in $group.

Restrict this new operator to FCV 4.4.

{panel:title=Downstream Change Summary|titleBGColor=#239eb0|bgColor=#c2d2c2}
I enhanced the EC2 instance profile readiness check again. You should update the version in https://github.com/mongodb-labs/drivers-evergreen-tools
{panel}
h2. Description of Linked Ticket
aws_e2e_ecs.js tries to check the availability of the IMDSv2 execution role but the check does not appear to be enough. It should be improved to check both the role name and that credentials are available.

